// update package
▶ sudo apt-get update
// check version python
▶ python3 --version

// ustanowka pip iz pythona
▶ python3 -m pip install --user --upgrade pip

// check pip version
▶ python3 -m pip --version

// install virtualenv
▶ python3 -m pip install --user virtualenv

// stworenia venv z nazwoju venv
▶ python3 -m virtualenv env

// zapusk wirtualnogo seredowyszcza
▶ source env/bin/activate

// (venv) proviriajem jakyj pytnon wykorystowujetsisa bo po defoltu bez "env"
▶ which python
/home/danj/dj/env/bin/python

▶ where python
/home/danj/dj/env/bin/python
/usr/bin/python

// (venv) deactivate virtualenv
deactivate

// (venv) check installed package 
▶ pip3 freeze

// (venv) Installing packages
▶ pip install namePackage
▶ pip install namePackage="2.18.4"

// delete pacgage but not dependency.If wont all install pip-autoremove
▶ pip3 uninstall namePackage

// Listing Packages
▶ pip list

// Uninstalling Packages
▶ pip uninstall namePackage

// pokazaty jaki paczku mozna obnowyty
▶ pip list --outdated

// upgrading packages
▶ pip install --upgrade requests

// (venv) spisok zawisomistej my jogo tworym szob potim widpalyty lehko projekt
▶ pip3 freeze > requirements.txt

// (venv) instalacja z konkretnogo pliku wsich zawisimostej
▶ pip install -r requirements.txt

// Command Completion
▶ pip completion --zsh >> ~/.zprofile

-----------------------------------------------------------------

// install pip-autoremove
pip install pip-autoremove
// remove "requests" plus its dependencies:
pip-autoremove packageName -y

Due to the way most Linux distributions are handling the Python 3 migration, Linux users using the system Python without creating a virtual environment first should replace the python command in this tutorial with python3 and the pip command with pip3 --user. Do not run any of the commands in this tutorial with sudo: if you get a permissions error, come back to the section on creating virtual environments, set one up, and then continue with the tutorial as writte

pip defaults to installing Python packages to a system directory (such as /usr/local/lib/python3.4). This requires root access.
--user makes pip install packages in your home directory instead, which doesn't require any special privileges.

